result.execSummary:
The defendant William T. Atkinson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

[MK] case called at 8:40am.
Defendant William T. Atkinson in court.  ADA Monica Hall appears for the State of Wisconsin.  
Opening Statements given by ADA Hall.

R.N.- sworn & testifies
--direct examination by ADA Hall
--cross examination by Mr. Atkinson
--redirect examination by ADA Hall

Officer Michele Martin- sworn & testifies
--direct examination by ADA Hall 
--State's Exhibit #1:  disc containing video/audio footage from Officer Martin's Axon camera- offered & received
--cross examination by Mr. Atkinson

Officer Ryan Weston- sworn & testifies
--direct examination by ADA Hall
--cross examination by Mr. Atkinson
State rests at 10:16am.

William T. Atkinson II- sworn & testifies
--the Court finds that Mr. Atkinson exercising hthe right to testify is done freely, voluntarily and intelligently 
--direct testimony given by Mr. Atkinson
--cross examination by ADA Hall 
Evidence closed at 10:28pm
Closing arguments given by ADA Hall, by Mr. Atkinson.

The Court finds Mr. Atkinson- guilty of Count #1, Resisting/Obstructing an Officer.
The Court finds Mr.Atkinson guilty of Count #2, Disorderly Conduct.
The Court orders that Judgment of Conviction is to be entered.
Sentencing arguments are given. 

On both Count #1 & #2, the Court withholds sentence and places Mr. Atkinson on Probation for one year, with conditions: 
--to undergo AODA assessment and follow through with treatment recommendations
--to undergo any other assessment, treatment and counseling as required by the Agent
--no possession or consumption of alcohol or illegal drugs
--no presence in bars, taverns, liquor stores
--no acts or threats of violence 
--to comply with DNA sample provision upon demand 
--to pay costs, fees, assessments, surcharges ($443 per count) 

The Court requires Mr. Atkinson to report to the Probation Office by 12:00 noon today.  
recess 10:52am.

[MK] case called at 4:22pm. 
Defendant William T. Atkinson in court.  ADA Theresa Beck appears for the State of Wisconsin.
Both parties indicate that they are prepared to proceed to Court Trial as scheduled.
The Court verifies with the parties that it intends to proceed to trial on this case on Friday, March 31st.  Both parties confirm their availability on Friday.
ADA Beck indicates that the State intends to call two officer-witnesses and a citizen witness. 
Mr. Atkinson indicates that he intends to testify. 
The Court reviews right to counsel.
The Court informs Mr. Atkinson of his right to remain silent.
The Court explains trial procedure including that Mr. Atkinson, including that he will have the right to cross examine the State's witnesses and to call witnesses and testify/not testify himself. 
Mr. Atkinson indicates that he understand the elements of the crime. 
ADA Beck indicates that the State seeks to admit statements of the Defendant. ADA Beck provides a summary of the intended statements that are within the discovery provided to Mr. Atkinson.
Mr. Atkinson indicates that he feels confident that he has received all discovery. 
The Court concludes that there is no Miranda-Goodchild issue with the intended statements. 
recess 4:31pm.

[JK] case called at 9:21am
Defendant William T. Atkinson in court. ADA Jeffery Shock appears for the State of Wisconsin.
This case is scheduled for Final Status Scheduling Conference today.
Court reviews right to counsel. Mr. Atkinson waives this right; Court confirms Mr. Atkinsons continuing this waiver of counsel and finds him competent to represent himself.
ADA Shock indicates that the State is not prepared to proceed to Trial next week as scheduled. The victim will be out of state until 3/7/17.
In response to the Courts inquiry, ADA Shock indicates that a Subpoena was generated and it seems likely that it has already been served.
The State is requesting to adjourn trial. Mr. Atkinson objects and states his desire for a speedy resolution and indicates that there may be complications with his work.
The Cout notes that Mr Atkinson has now demanded a speedy trial.
The Court reviews the records and verifies that there have been no previous adjournments. The Court grants adjournment and will schedule a trial within the next 60 days.
ADA Shock indicates that the States plans to call 3 witnesses, including 2 officers and the victim.
Mr. Atkinson does not intend to call additional witnesses.
The Court encourages the parties to make efforts to see if there is a possible resolution of the case.
recess: 9:37am
